  "answer": "Required eval accounting fields typically include: token counts, provider/model IDs, estimated price, and latency percentiles. Token counts should separately report input/prompt tokens, output/completion tokens, and total tokens when available, because pricing and debugging often depend on direction. Provider/model IDs should identify the actual provider and model used for the run, including version or deployment name if relevant, so results are reproducible. Estimated price should be computed from the provider's pricing schedule using the recorded token counts and any other billable units; it should be labeled as estimated because discounts, rounding, caching, retries, or provider-side accounting can change the final bill. Latency p50, p90, and p95 are percentile measurements over a set of requests: p50 is the median latency, p90 means 90% of requests completed at or below that time, and p95 means 95% completed at or below that time. These latency fields should specify units, usually milliseconds, and should be based on a clearly defined measurement window and request population.",
